WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:08.640 --> 00:00:10.023
- Good morning, everybody.

00:00:11.310 --> 00:00:13.280
So today's lecture is called

00:00:13.280 --> 00:00:16.770
The Denouement of
Humanitarian Intervention,

00:00:16.770 --> 00:00:20.713
and it's mainly gonna be focused on Libya,

00:00:23.030 --> 00:00:24.830
though we'll see, we'll look elsewhere

00:00:24.830 --> 00:00:26.973
in the Arab Spring as well.

00:00:28.940 --> 00:00:32.850
Let's start at the end, though.

00:00:32.850 --> 00:00:35.363
This is Libya late last year.

00:05:44.370 --> 00:05:49.080
- So that was the situation in late 2018.

00:05:49.080 --> 00:05:51.200
If anything, it's worse today.

00:05:51.200 --> 00:05:53.910
There was supposed to be elections held

00:05:53.910 --> 00:05:56.720
which couldn't be held
because of the fighting

00:05:56.720 --> 00:06:01.720
and Haftar has mounted
successive assaults on Tripoli,

00:06:01.970 --> 00:06:04.980
and so the country is in a continuing

00:06:04.980 --> 00:06:07.133
stalemate failed state.

00:06:08.260 --> 00:06:10.050
So that tells you what happened,

00:06:10.050 --> 00:06:12.370
it didn't tell you anything
about why it happened

00:06:12.370 --> 00:06:16.973
and what we should infer from
why it happened, and that's,

00:06:18.180 --> 00:06:20.920
the way into today's agenda.

00:06:20.920 --> 00:06:23.313
We're gonna ask how and why it happened,

00:06:24.460 --> 00:06:26.540
and then we're gonna
look at the implications

00:06:26.540 --> 00:06:30.140
for the prospects for
humanitarian intervention efforts

00:06:30.140 --> 00:06:33.580
going forward, the
stability and future shape

00:06:33.580 --> 00:06:37.090
of the Middle East, and
the ability of the US

00:06:37.090 --> 00:06:39.550
to be a force for good internationally

00:06:41.360 --> 00:06:44.380
and how that has been impacted by this,

00:06:44.380 --> 00:06:47.330
what's happened over the last nine years

00:06:47.330 --> 00:06:49.933
since we begun that action.

00:06:51.110 --> 00:06:55.090
But let's begin by picking up
the thread of responsibility

00:06:55.090 --> 00:07:00.090
to protect that I lectured
about a couple of weeks ago.

00:07:00.400 --> 00:07:02.980
And you'll remember that this was all

00:07:02.980 --> 00:07:07.083
in the shadow of Rwanda, and then Kosovo.

00:07:08.174 --> 00:07:13.077
The NATO forces had
gone into Kosovo in 1999

00:07:14.270 --> 00:07:19.270
without UN authorization

00:07:19.400 --> 00:07:22.170
when no NATO country had been threatened,

00:07:22.170 --> 00:07:24.530
and this has produced
a lot of hand-wringing

00:07:24.530 --> 00:07:27.570
in the international community that led

00:07:27.570 --> 00:07:30.103
the Prime Minister of Sweden,

00:07:31.690 --> 00:07:34.180
don't know by what
legitimacy he had to do this,

00:07:34.180 --> 00:07:37.000
but he appointed an
international commission

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:39.870
which concluded that the NATO action

00:07:39.870 --> 00:07:42.770
had been illegal but legitimate.

00:07:42.770 --> 00:07:46.330
We had considerable debate
about what that might mean,

00:07:46.330 --> 00:07:49.810
and they did at the time as well.

00:07:49.810 --> 00:07:53.872
It was eventually
followed in 2005 at the UN

00:07:53.872 --> 00:07:55.960
by the adoption of something called

00:07:55.960 --> 00:07:58.740
the UN World Summit Outcome Document

00:07:58.740 --> 00:08:03.350
where they famously announced
that each individual state

00:08:03.350 --> 00:08:06.880
has a responsibility to
protect its populations

00:08:06.880 --> 00:08:10.110
from genocide, war
crimes, ethnic cleansing,

00:08:10.110 --> 00:08:12.340
and crimes against humanity.

00:08:12.340 --> 00:08:16.880
They took it upon the UN
to be the enforcer of this

00:08:16.880 --> 00:08:19.927
and said, "We are prepared
to take collective action

00:08:19.927 --> 00:08:21.967
"in a timely and decisive manner

00:08:21.967 --> 00:08:26.197
"through the Security Council
on a case-by-case basis,

00:08:26.197 --> 00:08:29.857
"and in cooperation with
relevant regional organizations

00:08:29.857 --> 00:08:32.920
"should other means be inadequate."

00:08:32.920 --> 00:08:37.129
And I pointed out that R2P had
a number of notable features,

00:08:37.129 --> 00:08:40.640
one that it was binding
not only on signatories,

00:08:40.640 --> 00:08:45.333
but on non-signatories
as well, unlike the ICC.

00:08:46.550 --> 00:08:50.820
It's restricted to severe
human rights abuses,

00:08:50.820 --> 00:08:53.520
genocide, crimes against
humanity, war crimes,

00:08:53.520 --> 00:08:57.583
and ethnic cleansing even though
others had pushed for more.

00:08:58.650 --> 00:09:00.840
It was a big departure for the UN

00:09:00.840 --> 00:09:04.520
because its focus on what
was going on within countries

00:09:04.520 --> 00:09:08.210
seemed to live in considerable
tension, to put it mildly,

00:09:08.210 --> 00:09:12.600
with the UN's hardboiled
recognition of the independence

00:09:12.600 --> 00:09:16.520
of countries and a remit
that was only about

00:09:16.520 --> 00:09:19.380
in maintaining international
peace and security

00:09:19.380 --> 00:09:22.433
and not being concerned with
what went on within countries.

00:09:24.230 --> 00:09:26.110
I pointed out that it was not binding

00:09:26.110 --> 00:09:28.008
on the Security Council.

00:09:28.008 --> 00:09:29.990
The responsibility to protect

00:09:29.990 --> 00:09:33.170
is the responsibility of
governments to protect

00:09:33.170 --> 00:09:35.330
populations under their control,

00:09:35.330 --> 00:09:38.610
but it's not a responsibility
of the social security

00:09:38.610 --> 00:09:41.080
necessarily to intervene.

00:09:41.080 --> 00:09:44.493
It gives wide latitude in a case-by-case,

00:09:46.980 --> 00:09:50.590
case-by-case basis, and
that the early opposition

00:09:50.590 --> 00:09:53.433
of the non-aligned movement
and the grumbling in the

00:09:55.040 --> 00:09:58.880
African Union was a
portent of things to come.

00:09:58.880 --> 00:09:59.930
And the things to come

00:09:59.930 --> 00:10:02.480
are what we're gonna
be talking about today.

00:10:02.480 --> 00:10:04.890
I also mentioned some early tests

00:10:04.890 --> 00:10:07.373
in Sudan and Kenya and Guinea,

00:10:08.420 --> 00:10:12.550
once the idea of R2P had been adopted,

00:10:12.550 --> 00:10:17.020
and also in Libya, in February of 2011,

00:10:18.640 --> 00:10:20.560
February 26th in particular,

00:10:20.560 --> 00:10:23.900
this is after the outbreak
of the Arab Spring,

00:10:23.900 --> 00:10:28.900
and once the conflict
in Libya was under way,

00:10:30.870 --> 00:10:34.950
that first of all unanimously
referred Gaddafi to the ICC,

00:10:34.950 --> 00:10:37.810
the first time a Security
Council had done that,

00:10:37.810 --> 00:10:40.650
somewhat hypocritically as I said because

00:10:40.650 --> 00:10:44.950
countries like the US don't
recognize its jurisdiction

00:10:44.950 --> 00:10:46.560
over their own nationals,

00:10:46.560 --> 00:10:48.710
but they were happy to
refer Gaddafi there.

00:10:50.410 --> 00:10:53.600
And they also mentioned the notion of

00:10:53.600 --> 00:10:55.623
responsibility to protect.

00:10:56.810 --> 00:11:00.080
And they imposed an arms embargo sanctions

00:11:00.080 --> 00:11:05.080
and urged that he'd be subject
to criminal prosecution,

00:11:07.340 --> 00:11:11.203
but the first real test was
actually the following month,

00:11:12.230 --> 00:11:16.962
when the UN substituted

00:11:16.962 --> 00:11:20.230
Security Council Resolution 1970

00:11:20.230 --> 00:11:24.140
with Security Council Resolution 1973,

00:11:24.140 --> 00:11:27.310
which we're gonna spend a
considerable bit of time on.

00:11:27.310 --> 00:11:30.690
But first, it's very
important to get some grip

00:11:30.690 --> 00:11:34.440
of what was actually going
on in the Arab Spring,

00:11:34.440 --> 00:11:37.970
because it was widely
misinterpreted at the time

00:11:37.970 --> 00:11:40.580
particularly in major countries,

00:11:40.580 --> 00:11:43.840
and the conventional wisdom
about what was going on

00:11:43.840 --> 00:11:47.040
turned out to be wildly wrong.

00:11:47.040 --> 00:11:50.470
So let me just give you a snippet
of the conventional wisdom

00:11:50.470 --> 00:11:52.763
and then we'll see what
was really going on.

00:11:54.770 --> 00:11:57.220
- While the uprising across the
Middle East and North Africa

00:11:57.220 --> 00:12:00.010
did not take place during
a specific calendar season,

00:12:00.010 --> 00:12:03.150
they were commonly referred
to as the Arab Spring,

00:12:03.150 --> 00:12:05.773
an allusion to the so
called Prague Spring,

00:12:05.773 --> 00:12:09.942
a 1968 democratic revolution
in Czechoslovakia.

00:12:09.942 --> 00:12:13.820
(uptempo drum music)

00:12:13.820 --> 00:12:16.540
The Arab Spring timeline began in Tunisia,

00:12:16.540 --> 00:12:18.640
a country that had been
under the allegedly corrupt

00:12:18.640 --> 00:12:22.380
and authoritarian rule of
President Zine El Abidine Ben Ali

00:12:22.380 --> 00:12:24.220
for more than two decades.

00:12:24.220 --> 00:12:28.150
On December 17th, 2010,
a working class vendor

00:12:28.150 --> 00:12:30.330
named Mohamed Bouazizi was approached

00:12:30.330 --> 00:12:33.940
by Tunisian authorities
about his unlicensed cart.

00:12:33.940 --> 00:12:35.400
He offered to pay a fine,

00:12:35.400 --> 00:12:37.490
but instead, his vegetables
were confiscated,

00:12:37.490 --> 00:12:40.260
and he was publicly
humiliated by the police.

00:12:40.260 --> 00:12:42.487
In a short protest,
Bouazizi stood in front of

00:12:42.487 --> 00:12:46.670
the local governor's office
and set himself on fire.

00:12:46.670 --> 00:12:49.223
He died from his injuries on January 4th.

00:12:51.289 --> 00:12:54.680
(dramatic music)

00:12:54.680 --> 00:12:57.300
Bouazizi became a martyr
who inspired others

00:12:57.300 --> 00:12:58.680
who were suffering from unemployment

00:12:58.680 --> 00:13:00.680
at the hands of a corrupt government.

00:13:00.680 --> 00:13:03.166
His death sparked a Tunisian revolution

00:13:03.166 --> 00:13:06.390
in which protesters armed
themselves not only with signs,

00:13:06.390 --> 00:13:09.400
but with cell phones,
allowing the protests

00:13:09.400 --> 00:13:12.390
to spread at social media speed.

00:13:12.390 --> 00:13:15.620
On January 11th, the week
after Bouazizi's death,

00:13:15.620 --> 00:13:17.490
Tunisia's government fell apart,

00:13:17.490 --> 00:13:21.113
and the disgraced President
Ben Ali fled the country.

00:13:22.040 --> 00:13:24.010
The videos of the successful uprising

00:13:24.010 --> 00:13:26.760
shared via social media
raise global awareness

00:13:26.760 --> 00:13:28.680
of the protests themselves.

00:13:28.680 --> 00:13:32.046
State-run news organizations
were barely able to keep up.

00:13:32.046 --> 00:13:34.320
The speed and success of the protests

00:13:34.320 --> 00:13:36.370
inspired others across the region.

00:13:36.370 --> 00:13:38.875
Throughout January,
protests erupted in Algeria,

00:13:38.875 --> 00:13:41.140
Jordan and Oman.

00:13:41.140 --> 00:13:44.560
By January 25th, the
movement reached Egypt,

00:13:44.560 --> 00:13:48.230
followed by Syria, Yemen, Iraq, Libya,

00:13:48.230 --> 00:13:49.973
and several other countries.

00:13:50.860 --> 00:13:53.950
On February 11th, the Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak

00:13:53.950 --> 00:13:56.830
stepped down, and by the end of the year,

00:13:56.830 --> 00:13:58.843
Yemen's government was overthrown.

00:13:59.881 --> 00:14:01.920
(people chanting)

00:14:01.920 --> 00:14:04.740
As was Libya's, ending the dictatorship

00:14:04.740 --> 00:14:07.607
and the life of their
leader Muammar Gaddafi,

00:14:07.607 --> 00:14:11.143
who was captured and killed
by Libyan rebel militia.

00:14:13.170 --> 00:14:16.380
- So that's the conventional
reading of each of the

00:14:17.750 --> 00:14:20.402
Arab Spring that it erupted in Tunisia

00:14:20.402 --> 00:14:23.850
and then just basically
spread like wildfire

00:14:23.850 --> 00:14:25.800
across the Middle East and North Africa,

00:14:25.800 --> 00:14:29.240
and it's one of the reasons
there was so much enthusiasm

00:14:29.240 --> 00:14:30.943
for it in the West.

00:14:31.860 --> 00:14:33.940
But it was a fundamental misreading,

00:14:33.940 --> 00:14:37.610
and just to give you one
very important illustration

00:14:37.610 --> 00:14:39.710
that bears on what's coming next,

00:14:39.710 --> 00:14:44.050
it was a misreading of
what was going on in Egypt.

00:14:44.050 --> 00:14:48.030
Now everybody could remember
at the turn of 2011,

00:14:48.030 --> 00:14:51.700
the eruption of protests
in Tahrir Square in Cairo,

00:14:51.700 --> 00:14:55.130
millions and millions of
protesters, supporters.

00:14:55.130 --> 00:14:56.880
It started out peacefully,

00:14:56.880 --> 00:14:59.992
and then supporters of the Mubarak regime

00:14:59.992 --> 00:15:02.230
became involved in conflicts

00:15:02.230 --> 00:15:05.070
with the opponents of the regime,

00:15:05.070 --> 00:15:08.090
and they were largely
middle class secular people.

00:15:08.090 --> 00:15:10.930
We tend to, we now with hindsight,

00:15:10.930 --> 00:15:12.527
we think about Morsi's

00:15:16.070 --> 00:15:19.130
Muslim Brotherhood
government being overthrown

00:15:19.130 --> 00:15:24.130
two years later, but at
the time of the eruption,

00:15:24.290 --> 00:15:28.870
it was largely a secular
opposition movement

00:15:28.870 --> 00:15:33.830
opposed to Mubarak,
calling for regime change.

00:15:33.830 --> 00:15:36.450
And I'll just show you
a couple of videos there

00:15:36.450 --> 00:15:40.523
that start to give a hint of
how the conventional reading,

00:15:41.600 --> 00:15:44.963
conventional wisdom was was misleading.

00:15:44.963 --> 00:15:47.796
(people chanting)

00:16:00.657 --> 00:16:04.907
(men speaking in foreign language)

00:16:13.051 --> 00:16:18.051
(people speaking in foreign
language and whistling)

00:16:29.219 --> 00:16:32.052
(people chanting)

00:17:10.087 --> 00:17:14.254
(man singing in foreign language)

00:17:23.658 --> 00:17:26.557
- So what was unusual there is,

00:17:26.557 --> 00:17:29.830
and if I played more,
you'd see even more of it,

00:17:29.830 --> 00:17:31.510
is that from the beginning,

00:17:31.510 --> 00:17:36.110
the military were very supportive
of these demonstrations

00:17:36.110 --> 00:17:38.490
that were going on in Tahrir Square,

00:17:38.490 --> 00:17:41.330
and indeed as time went
on, it became clear

00:17:41.330 --> 00:17:45.280
that the military was
behind the regime change.

00:17:45.280 --> 00:17:46.400
- [Matt] President Hosni Mubarak

00:17:46.400 --> 00:17:48.592
will meet the demands of protestors,

00:17:48.592 --> 00:17:51.595
military and ruling party
officials said Thursday.

00:17:51.595 --> 00:17:53.430
It's the strongest indication yet

00:17:53.430 --> 00:17:55.138
that Egypt's longtime president

00:17:55.138 --> 00:17:56.727
may be about to give up power

00:17:56.727 --> 00:17:59.294
and that the armed forces
were seizing control.

00:17:59.294 --> 00:18:01.802
A military commander told
thousand of protestors

00:18:01.802 --> 00:18:03.128
in Central Tahrir Square,

00:18:03.128 --> 00:18:05.262
"All your demands will be met today."

00:18:05.262 --> 00:18:06.632
Some in the crowd held up their hands

00:18:06.632 --> 00:18:09.719
in V for victory signs,
shouting, "God is great."

00:18:09.719 --> 00:18:12.057
The military's supreme
council was meeting Thursday

00:18:12.057 --> 00:18:14.210
without the Commander in Chief Mubarak,

00:18:14.210 --> 00:18:16.227
and announced on state TV its support

00:18:16.227 --> 00:18:18.411
of the legitimate demands of the people.

00:18:18.411 --> 00:18:20.418
A spokesman read a
statement that the council

00:18:20.418 --> 00:18:22.631
was in permanent session to explore

00:18:22.631 --> 00:18:24.497
what measures and
arrangements could be made

00:18:24.497 --> 00:18:26.889
to safeguard the nation, its achievements,

00:18:26.889 --> 00:18:28.957
and the ambitions of its great people.

00:18:28.957 --> 00:18:31.200
The head of the ruling party
told the Associated Press

00:18:31.200 --> 00:18:33.526
that he expects Mubarak will
address the people tonight

00:18:33.526 --> 00:18:36.280
to respond to protesters' demands.

00:18:36.280 --> 00:18:38.483
Matt Friedman, The Associated Press.

00:18:44.784 --> 00:18:47.362
- Either this is the first Arab revolution

00:18:47.362 --> 00:18:48.729
of the 21st century,

00:18:48.729 --> 00:18:51.032
either this is the first Arab revolution

00:18:51.032 --> 00:18:51.865
of the 21st century, or it
will be brutally suppressed.

00:18:55.757 --> 00:18:57.688
- [Reporter] Tense new
beginnings for Tunisia,

00:18:57.688 --> 00:18:58.747
its Arab neighbors nervous
of how revolutionary feelings

00:19:01.563 --> 00:19:02.815
could spread.

00:19:02.815 --> 00:19:06.331
Mubarak's deposed,
Egypt's 18 day revolution

00:19:06.331 --> 00:19:08.060
defies all expectation.

00:19:08.060 --> 00:19:11.670
- Rarely can a military
takeover have been greeted

00:19:11.670 --> 00:19:14.533
with such enthusiasm,
as it is on the streets

00:19:14.533 --> 00:19:16.033
of Cairo tonight.

00:19:17.854 --> 00:19:21.340
- So there again, you see
this enormous enthusiasm

00:19:21.340 --> 00:19:23.420
for this military takeover,

00:19:23.420 --> 00:19:25.663
which then promised elections.

00:19:27.200 --> 00:19:29.834
And in the elections,

00:19:29.834 --> 00:19:34.440
initially, the Muslim
Brotherhood was not going to run.

00:19:34.440 --> 00:19:35.940
They said they would not run because

00:19:35.940 --> 00:19:39.420
they were the only organized
political party in Egypt,

00:19:39.420 --> 00:19:41.260
and there was a general perception

00:19:41.260 --> 00:19:44.590
it would be unfair for them to have

00:19:44.590 --> 00:19:46.270
such a big head start,

00:19:46.270 --> 00:19:48.250
but they soon changed their mind

00:19:48.250 --> 00:19:53.250
and the military allowed them
to run, and Morsi easily won.

00:19:53.450 --> 00:19:57.770
But the puzzle is why
did the Egyptian military

00:19:57.770 --> 00:20:00.740
get behind this revolution?

00:20:00.740 --> 00:20:03.093
It's not what the military typically does.

00:20:03.970 --> 00:20:07.420
Mubarak had a long history of association

00:20:07.420 --> 00:20:09.110
with the military.

00:20:09.110 --> 00:20:14.110
And so this really is a corruption story

00:20:14.240 --> 00:20:18.237
spelled out in Sarah Chayes'
book "Thieves of State:

00:20:18.237 --> 00:20:21.547
"Why Corruption Threatens
Global Security".

00:20:23.140 --> 00:20:25.760
That book is principally about Afghanistan

00:20:25.760 --> 00:20:27.730
where she spent 10 years,

00:20:27.730 --> 00:20:31.100
and for her main thesis in the book,

00:20:31.100 --> 00:20:32.900
which is sort of orthogonal to what

00:20:32.900 --> 00:20:35.620
we're doing here today,
but I'll just mention it,

00:20:35.620 --> 00:20:39.670
her main thesis is that
insurgent movements

00:20:39.670 --> 00:20:42.880
are fed by corruption,
that people on the ground,

00:20:42.880 --> 00:20:45.260
citizenrys hate corruption,

00:20:45.260 --> 00:20:50.260
and if insurgent movements
promised to get rid of corruption

00:20:50.450 --> 00:20:52.010
the people will support them.

00:20:52.010 --> 00:20:55.140
And she had been trying to
convince Petraeus, McChrystal

00:20:55.140 --> 00:20:59.010
and others that any effective
counterinsurgency movement

00:20:59.010 --> 00:21:01.890
in Afghanistan would
have to focus centrally

00:21:01.890 --> 00:21:03.660
on getting rid of corruption

00:21:03.660 --> 00:21:07.850
if it was ever gonna get
anywhere, and she eventually got,

00:21:07.850 --> 00:21:09.240
had some headway.

00:21:09.240 --> 00:21:12.460
But her chapter about Egypt
tells a somewhat different

00:21:12.460 --> 00:21:14.570
and more interesting story in some ways

00:21:14.570 --> 00:21:17.690
which is that the Egyptian military

00:21:19.920 --> 00:21:23.710
had a long history of being involved

00:21:23.710 --> 00:21:27.320
in a certain kind of
corruption with a difference.

00:21:27.320 --> 00:21:29.623
So if you go back to 1970,

00:21:31.870 --> 00:21:36.170
the 1967 and '73 wars against Israel,

00:21:36.170 --> 00:21:39.010
the Egyptian military
had been badly humiliated

00:21:39.010 --> 00:21:44.010
by being defeated by the
Israelis, and as a result of that,

00:21:45.360 --> 00:21:50.360
they partly blamed the
inept Egyptian state

00:21:51.560 --> 00:21:54.180
and its inability to deliver the things

00:21:54.180 --> 00:21:55.860
that the military needed.

00:21:55.860 --> 00:21:58.573
So they decided to essentially,

00:21:59.790 --> 00:22:02.790
you might call it, sort of go rogue,

00:22:02.790 --> 00:22:05.510
and they created their own second economy

00:22:05.510 --> 00:22:09.940
to create all of their own
supply lines for the military.

00:22:09.940 --> 00:22:13.010
And the thought was that never again

00:22:13.010 --> 00:22:16.590
was the military gonna be
under-resourced and under-prepared

00:22:16.590 --> 00:22:18.900
in a future war.

00:22:18.900 --> 00:22:20.417
But as things go,

00:22:20.417 --> 00:22:24.030
and you get mission creep
in all matters in life,

00:22:24.030 --> 00:22:26.730
they then discovered,
many of these generals,

00:22:26.730 --> 00:22:28.930
that they could actually
make a lot of money

00:22:30.220 --> 00:22:34.570
in this second economy,
and so it became a lot of

00:22:35.900 --> 00:22:38.510
essentially a kind of black market economy

00:22:38.510 --> 00:22:41.360
through which these generals became rich.

00:22:41.360 --> 00:22:45.400
However, they were
fairly discreet about it,

00:22:45.400 --> 00:22:49.500
they didn't flaunt their wealth very much

00:22:49.500 --> 00:22:54.500
and they didn't outrage
the population that much.

00:22:54.600 --> 00:22:59.600
However, what happens in
the heyday of neoliberalism

00:23:00.770 --> 00:23:04.870
and the Washington Consensus
is that other Egyptian elites

00:23:04.870 --> 00:23:09.540
also decide to get rich, and
particularly Mubarak's son,

00:23:09.540 --> 00:23:12.880
Gamal Mubarak was a sort of London playboy

00:23:12.880 --> 00:23:16.030
with lots of fancy cars,
and he and his friends

00:23:16.030 --> 00:23:19.083
came back to Egypt and they,

00:23:21.790 --> 00:23:23.440
they did flaunt their wealth,

00:23:23.440 --> 00:23:26.980
and so they had the Lamborghinis
driving around Cairo

00:23:26.980 --> 00:23:30.530
and the playboy clubs
and all the rest of this,

00:23:30.530 --> 00:23:33.500
and this partly outraged the military

00:23:33.500 --> 00:23:37.480
and also made the military worried

00:23:37.480 --> 00:23:40.750
that there was gonna be a reaction against

00:23:40.750 --> 00:23:42.900
this kind of corruption.

00:23:42.900 --> 00:23:47.900
So they got behind the coup,

00:23:48.460 --> 00:23:51.320
behind the Arab Spring
because they really,

00:23:51.320 --> 00:23:56.320
they wanted to get rid
of the Mubarak regime.

00:23:56.400 --> 00:23:59.440
And furthermore, they
were very happy for Morsi

00:23:59.440 --> 00:24:03.230
to be elected because in their view,

00:24:03.230 --> 00:24:07.380
he would be the agent of
cleansing the old regime,

00:24:07.380 --> 00:24:10.900
and they would be able to
keep their hands clean,

00:24:10.900 --> 00:24:13.692
which he then did because Morsi ran,

00:24:13.692 --> 00:24:17.790
he played the typical
Sarah Chayes playbook,

00:24:17.790 --> 00:24:21.350
he ran as being a cleaner up of corruption

00:24:21.350 --> 00:24:22.543
who would get rid of,

00:24:23.460 --> 00:24:26.690
who would drain the swamp, so to speak.

00:24:26.690 --> 00:24:31.080
And he set about doing that,
going after the old regime,

00:24:31.080 --> 00:24:36.000
and indeed, Mubarak and his children were

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:40.150
convicted of various corruption
charges and were in and out,

00:24:40.150 --> 00:24:42.482
and the sons were in and out of prison

00:24:42.482 --> 00:24:45.970
for many of the next several years.

00:24:45.970 --> 00:24:48.840
But once Mubarak had done,

00:24:48.840 --> 00:24:50.820
once Morsi had done that,

00:24:50.820 --> 00:24:52.900
the military had no more use for him.

00:24:52.900 --> 00:24:57.900
And so when people came
dissatisfied with him,

00:24:58.670 --> 00:25:01.710
they had no problem getting rid of him,

00:25:01.710 --> 00:25:06.710
and General Sisi took over and
recreated a military regime,

00:25:07.870 --> 00:25:11.330
and that's what we've had
for the last several years.

00:25:11.330 --> 00:25:14.300
So there was a popular uprising,

00:25:14.300 --> 00:25:18.440
but people misunderstood
what was really going on,

00:25:18.440 --> 00:25:22.610
which was essentially the
military ridding themselves

00:25:22.610 --> 00:25:26.560
of liabilities and consolidating a regime

00:25:26.560 --> 00:25:28.633
over a couple of years.

00:25:29.700 --> 00:25:34.070
And so that was one form of
misreading what was going on

00:25:34.070 --> 00:25:35.850
in the Arab Spring.

00:25:35.850 --> 00:25:40.420
Another form is what happened in Libya,

00:25:40.420 --> 00:25:44.073
as we could also tell much
of the same story for Yemen,

00:25:45.650 --> 00:25:50.040
which is that people
widely mistook a civil war

00:25:52.390 --> 00:25:57.390
for a revolution, a civil
war for a popular uprising.

00:25:58.150 --> 00:26:03.150
So the Security Council Resolution

00:26:03.410 --> 00:26:05.913
that was adopted in March,

00:26:08.750 --> 00:26:12.970
1973, you can see it
was voted 10 yes, no no,

00:26:12.970 --> 00:26:17.970
with five abstentions, and
so nobody had opposed it

00:26:18.530 --> 00:26:22.950
whereas the one three weeks
earlier had been unanimous.

00:26:22.950 --> 00:26:25.250
And it established no-fly zones,

00:26:25.250 --> 00:26:28.850
this is when violence had erupted.

00:26:28.850 --> 00:26:32.230
It excluded the introduction
of foreign ground forces.

00:26:32.230 --> 00:26:35.100
It authorized member
states acting nationally

00:26:35.100 --> 00:26:37.810
or through regional
organizations or arrangements

00:26:37.810 --> 00:26:41.490
to take all necessary
measures to protect civilians

00:26:41.490 --> 00:26:45.400
and civilian populations
under threat of attack.

00:26:45.400 --> 00:26:50.220
And it created an exception
to the resolution it passed

00:26:50.220 --> 00:26:54.200
three weeks earlier, so that,

00:26:54.200 --> 00:26:57.400
which had imposed an arms embargo

00:26:57.400 --> 00:27:02.400
in order to enable the UN supported forces

00:27:03.036 --> 00:27:05.640
to arm the rebels.

00:27:05.640 --> 00:27:09.530
And so that was a signal
of what was to come.

00:27:09.530 --> 00:27:14.530
So here you had, in February 26,

00:27:14.790 --> 00:27:18.152
you had a resolution passed,
including an arms embargo,

00:27:18.152 --> 00:27:22.910
three weeks later, you
have a modification of that

00:27:22.910 --> 00:27:26.280
and a much more
aggressively interventionist

00:27:26.280 --> 00:27:30.100
but still containment-oriented regime.

00:27:30.100 --> 00:27:34.270
So one question is, well, what happened?

00:27:34.270 --> 00:27:35.103
Why?

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:40.833
Why did the UN authorize these
new actions in three weeks?

00:27:46.080 --> 00:27:49.513
And here's a clue to that action.

00:27:51.180 --> 00:27:53.493
Notice the dates on these documents.

00:27:54.810 --> 00:27:57.297
The Resolution 1970

00:28:00.427 --> 00:28:02.923
had been passed on February 26th,

00:28:04.010 --> 00:28:07.080
on March 10th, so this is a week later,

00:28:07.080 --> 00:28:11.010
a week before, two weeks
later, a week before

00:28:11.010 --> 00:28:13.800
the new resolution's gonna go ahead,

00:28:13.800 --> 00:28:15.983
you could read this in the New York Times,

00:28:16.817 --> 00:28:19.457
"Moving ahead of its
allies, France on Thursday

00:28:19.457 --> 00:28:21.597
"became the first country to recognize

00:28:21.597 --> 00:28:26.047
"Libya's rebel leadership in
the eastern city of Benghazi

00:28:26.047 --> 00:28:28.737
"and said it would soon
exchange ambassadors

00:28:28.737 --> 00:28:30.337
"with the insurgents.

00:28:30.337 --> 00:28:33.297
"The move was a victory for
the Libyan National Council

00:28:33.297 --> 00:28:36.827
"in its quest for recognition
and a setback for Gaddafi

00:28:36.827 --> 00:28:39.567
"who had been seeking
whatever international support

00:28:39.567 --> 00:28:42.587
"he could for as NATO members in Brussels

00:28:42.587 --> 00:28:46.267
"had begun debating the
possibility of imposing

00:28:46.267 --> 00:28:47.837
"a no-fly zone.

00:28:47.837 --> 00:28:51.970
"The French announcement came
as loyalist forces in Libya

00:28:53.787 --> 00:28:56.427
"claimed new successes against the rebels

00:28:56.427 --> 00:28:59.347
"west of the capital, while in the east,

00:28:59.347 --> 00:29:02.510
"loyalist forces renewed
ferocious attacks,"

00:29:02.510 --> 00:29:05.410
on several towns actually.

00:29:05.410 --> 00:29:10.090
So what this paragraph is concealing

00:29:10.090 --> 00:29:12.750
or not telling you is that when

00:29:14.080 --> 00:29:16.270
the first resolution had passed,

00:29:16.270 --> 00:29:19.520
it looked like Gaddafi was basically done.

00:29:19.520 --> 00:29:22.780
It looked, he had lost
control of all of the cities,

00:29:22.780 --> 00:29:25.940
and as a result of that,

00:29:25.940 --> 00:29:28.280
it looked like his days were numbered.

00:29:28.280 --> 00:29:31.550
Most people thought the
regime was crumbling.

00:29:31.550 --> 00:29:34.710
And the French and the
British and the Italians

00:29:34.710 --> 00:29:39.020
had big oil interests and
good relations with Gaddafi.

00:29:39.020 --> 00:29:40.843
Gaddafi, we forget,

00:29:42.140 --> 00:29:45.700
in the first decade of the
21st century had sort of,

00:29:45.700 --> 00:29:48.650
internationally speaking,
come in from the cold.

00:29:48.650 --> 00:29:53.650
He had given up the
Lockerbie bombers for trial,

00:29:53.810 --> 00:29:57.610
he had agreed to dismantle
his nuclear program,

00:29:57.610 --> 00:29:59.610
which he subsequently did,

00:29:59.610 --> 00:30:03.850
he helped with intelligence
against Afghanistan

00:30:03.850 --> 00:30:06.750
in the aftermath of 9/11,

00:30:06.750 --> 00:30:11.350
and actually also, his domestic
atrocities had diminished.

00:30:11.350 --> 00:30:14.170
If you look at most of the
human rights violations

00:30:14.170 --> 00:30:18.120
he's accused of, they're all
before the turn of the century.

00:30:18.120 --> 00:30:20.200
Didn't mean he'd become a nice guy,

00:30:20.200 --> 00:30:24.440
but he was a pretty run-of-the-mill
Middle Eastern dictator

00:30:27.962 --> 00:30:31.703
not as nasty as he had been in the 1990s.

00:30:34.160 --> 00:30:36.210
But now it looked like he was done,

00:30:36.210 --> 00:30:39.228
and so the question is
what was gonna happen

00:30:39.228 --> 00:30:42.760
to the oil relationships?

00:30:42.760 --> 00:30:46.160
And so the French decided
they better make nice

00:30:46.160 --> 00:30:48.500
with who's gonna be the new government,

00:30:48.500 --> 00:30:51.620
and so they started conversations,

00:30:51.620 --> 00:30:55.750
and these were brokered by a
French political philosopher

00:30:55.750 --> 00:30:58.910
by the name of Bernard-Henri Levy

00:30:58.910 --> 00:31:01.420
shows you why you should never
let political philosophers

00:31:01.420 --> 00:31:04.900
have too much influence in politics,

00:31:04.900 --> 00:31:08.820
and he started brokering meetings between

00:31:08.820 --> 00:31:11.940
the opposition groups and
the French government,

00:31:11.940 --> 00:31:13.890
Sarkozy's government.

00:31:13.890 --> 00:31:15.665
He was essentially telling them,

00:31:15.665 --> 00:31:19.030
"This is the government
that's taking over,"

00:31:19.030 --> 00:31:24.030
but after the first resolution had passed,

00:31:25.600 --> 00:31:27.730
the reality on the ground changed,

00:31:27.730 --> 00:31:30.090
and Gaddafi started winning again,

00:31:30.090 --> 00:31:34.080
and so they were then in
trouble because they had said

00:31:34.080 --> 00:31:38.020
on March 10th that France
recognized the Council

00:31:38.020 --> 00:31:41.560
as a sole legitimate
representative the Libyan people,

00:31:41.560 --> 00:31:44.860
it put France ahead of
other European powers

00:31:44.860 --> 00:31:47.560
that had been seeking ways
of supporting the rebels

00:31:47.560 --> 00:31:49.370
on toppling Gaddafi,

00:31:49.370 --> 00:31:51.720
normally European countries don't do that,

00:31:51.720 --> 00:31:54.050
so their aggressive
stance was seen as a way

00:31:54.050 --> 00:31:56.460
of showing commitment
to the popular uprising,

00:31:56.460 --> 00:31:59.320
so they said, but what
they were really doing

00:31:59.320 --> 00:32:02.110
was showing a commitment
to the what they thought

00:32:02.110 --> 00:32:04.830
was the emerging government of Libya.

00:32:04.830 --> 00:32:09.030
And you can see here how they spun it,

00:32:09.030 --> 00:32:12.040
the day that the resolution was passed.

00:32:12.040 --> 00:32:16.163
The resolution, allegedly
just about containment,

00:32:17.020 --> 00:32:20.600
passed a week after France
had already recognized

00:32:20.600 --> 00:32:23.893
the opposition as the
legitimate government of Libya.

00:32:24.990 --> 00:32:27.630
- [Tim] After being accused
of being slow to react

00:32:27.630 --> 00:32:30.370
to the revolutions in Tunisia and Egypt,

00:32:30.370 --> 00:32:32.560
the French president has moved quickly

00:32:32.560 --> 00:32:36.160
to silence his critics and
take the lead in reprisals

00:32:36.160 --> 00:32:38.260
against Colonel Gaddafi.

00:32:38.260 --> 00:32:41.860
Meeting representatives of the
rebels at the Elysee Palace,

00:32:41.860 --> 00:32:45.546
he promised them immediate
diplomatic recognition.

00:32:45.546 --> 00:32:48.170
(speaking foreign language)

00:32:48.170 --> 00:32:49.970
- [Interpreter] France has
expressed its satisfaction

00:32:49.970 --> 00:32:52.637
about the creation of the Libyan
National Transition Council

00:32:52.637 --> 00:32:54.742
and after this meeting
with President Sarkozy,

00:32:54.742 --> 00:32:56.580
I can say that France has recognized

00:32:56.580 --> 00:32:57.810
the Transitional National Council

00:32:57.810 --> 00:33:01.760
as the legitimate representation
of the Libyan people.

00:33:01.760 --> 00:33:03.980
- The French plan is reported to include

00:33:03.980 --> 00:33:08.190
proposing limited airstrikes
against key Gaddafi targets,

00:33:08.190 --> 00:33:12.160
such as his headquarters
and a military airbase.

00:33:12.160 --> 00:33:14.540
There was no official confirmation

00:33:14.540 --> 00:33:16.720
from President Sarkozy's office,

00:33:16.720 --> 00:33:19.610
and it's a highly controversial proposal

00:33:19.610 --> 00:33:21.850
that would meet with strong resistance

00:33:21.850 --> 00:33:24.260
from many European allies,

00:33:24.260 --> 00:33:28.300
who are also wary of giving
the rebel representatives

00:33:28.300 --> 00:33:31.464
diplomatic recognition at this stage.

00:33:31.464 --> 00:33:33.410
(speaking foreign language)

00:33:33.410 --> 00:33:35.650
- [Interpreter] That's a
decision by a single government.

00:33:35.650 --> 00:33:37.590
I think it's better for
us to listen to the stance

00:33:37.590 --> 00:33:39.373
of the entire European community.

00:33:41.030 --> 00:33:43.770
- [Tim] The Elysee Palace
says that Mr. Sarkozy

00:33:43.770 --> 00:33:45.630
is seeking legal authority

00:33:45.630 --> 00:33:48.380
to prevent the use of force by Gaddafi.

00:33:48.380 --> 00:33:51.150
It believes that jamming
his communications

00:33:51.150 --> 00:33:53.090
would be a good start.

00:33:53.090 --> 00:33:55.813
Tim Friend, Al Jazeera, Paris.

00:33:56.890 --> 00:33:58.600
- So there was, they were now,

00:33:58.600 --> 00:34:00.340
they were in a difficult spot

00:34:00.340 --> 00:34:03.320
because they had
recognized the opposition,

00:34:03.320 --> 00:34:05.650
but Gaddafi was now once
again winning the war

00:34:05.650 --> 00:34:08.510
and he was regaining
control of the cities,

00:34:08.510 --> 00:34:12.400
and he was indeed about to
regain control of Benghazi,

00:34:12.400 --> 00:34:16.950
and so what the French did was that they

00:34:18.470 --> 00:34:23.470
pushed very hard to
get a resolution passed

00:34:23.500 --> 00:34:26.120
that would allow them to depose Gaddafi

00:34:26.120 --> 00:34:28.340
because they realized that they had

00:34:29.320 --> 00:34:31.580
burned their bridges with him,

00:34:31.580 --> 00:34:35.450
and essentially, that
had become their agenda.

00:34:35.450 --> 00:34:39.350
And right after the resolution passed,

00:34:39.350 --> 00:34:43.610
they began massive bombing
almost immediately,

00:34:43.610 --> 00:34:46.180
so much so that the Arab League,

00:34:46.180 --> 00:34:49.888
you can see here, the next
day the resolution passed

00:34:49.888 --> 00:34:53.585
three days later, passed on the 17th,

00:34:53.585 --> 00:34:58.200
the Arab League was furious
as was the African Union

00:34:58.200 --> 00:35:01.200
who had gone along with this,

00:35:01.200 --> 00:35:05.530
and African Union countries
on the Security Council

00:35:05.530 --> 00:35:07.360
had even voted for it,

00:35:07.360 --> 00:35:12.180
and they saw that there was
a much more aggressive agenda

00:35:12.180 --> 00:35:16.550
going on and it was really
about getting rid of the regime.

00:35:16.550 --> 00:35:19.850
And indeed, a lot of reports,

00:35:19.850 --> 00:35:23.190
and I've given you the
jot and tittle of this

00:35:23.190 --> 00:35:27.330
in the reading for today,
a lot of the report,

00:35:27.330 --> 00:35:28.900
or the reading for two weeks ago,

00:35:28.900 --> 00:35:32.570
a lot of the reports about
imminent slaughter of civilians

00:35:32.570 --> 00:35:37.190
in Benghazi turned out to be
what we call fake news today,

00:35:37.190 --> 00:35:40.810
and there were very, first
of all, very few fatalities

00:35:40.810 --> 00:35:43.480
in the retaking of these cities,

00:35:43.480 --> 00:35:46.410
and almost no civilians were killed.

00:35:46.410 --> 00:35:51.380
Nonetheless, the hype for the
intervention was cranked up

00:35:51.380 --> 00:35:56.220
on the grounds that Gaddafi
was about to slaughter

00:35:56.220 --> 00:35:59.800
hundreds of thousands of
civilians in Benghazi.

00:35:59.800 --> 00:36:02.750
But I said at the outset that this,

00:36:02.750 --> 00:36:07.080
that everybody in the
West who was treating this

00:36:07.080 --> 00:36:10.890
as an Arab Spring
revolution were misreading

00:36:10.890 --> 00:36:13.263
that this was really a civil war.

00:36:14.170 --> 00:36:17.630
And the smoking gun comes
when you start to look at

00:36:17.630 --> 00:36:21.070
what was going on in the
Obama administration,

00:36:21.070 --> 00:36:25.470
because after all, Obama had run against,

00:36:25.470 --> 00:36:27.420
against endless wars.

00:36:27.420 --> 00:36:29.430
Obama had said that the, yes,

00:36:29.430 --> 00:36:31.920
Afghanistan had been a war of necessity,

00:36:31.920 --> 00:36:34.890
but the Iraq invasion
had been a war of choice.

00:36:34.890 --> 00:36:37.920
Unlike Hillary Clinton and unlike Kerry,

00:36:37.920 --> 00:36:40.403
he had not supported it in 2003,

00:36:41.312 --> 00:36:44.079
and he said America
should not get involved

00:36:44.079 --> 00:36:47.170
in these sorts of conflicts.

00:36:47.170 --> 00:36:51.020
And so who in the
administration was against it?

00:36:51.020 --> 00:36:55.990
Well, we'll see that in a second,

00:36:55.990 --> 00:36:59.570
but here's the smoking gun
that it was a civil war,

00:36:59.570 --> 00:37:02.300
who was leading the revolution?

00:37:02.300 --> 00:37:05.180
One is that Abdul Jalil

00:37:05.180 --> 00:37:08.390
was Gaddafi's former Justice Minister,

00:37:08.390 --> 00:37:12.073
Ali Aziz, Gaddafi's former
Ambassador to India,

00:37:13.132 --> 00:37:16.640
Mahmoud Jebril, his former
top economic advisor

00:37:16.640 --> 00:37:19.933
who was closely linked to
the oil multinationals,

00:37:21.060 --> 00:37:24.864
and the leaders of the so-called
Rebel Revolutionary Council

00:37:24.864 --> 00:37:29.500
included Abdul Younis who,
in the battle of Benghazi,

00:37:29.500 --> 00:37:32.100
had actually been on the
government's side initially

00:37:32.100 --> 00:37:33.670
and switched sides,

00:37:33.670 --> 00:37:38.670
and Omar Hariri, who had
no democratic credentials.

00:37:39.750 --> 00:37:43.617
Both of them had long
histories dating back to 1969

00:37:45.480 --> 00:37:49.120
of repressing democratic movements.

00:37:49.120 --> 00:37:51.523
So what happened here, what happened?

00:37:53.027 --> 00:37:55.220
As I said first of all,
February and March,

00:37:55.220 --> 00:37:58.510
from February to March,
things changed on the ground,

