Democrats had no alternative

00:54:15.200 --> 00:54:16.660
to the Bush Doctrine.

00:54:16.660 --> 00:54:20.845
I said this last time when we
talked about the deficiencies

00:54:20.845 --> 00:54:22.580
of the Bush Doctrine,

00:54:22.580 --> 00:54:24.720
but what was the democratic alternative?

00:54:24.720 --> 00:54:29.580
They had no well articulated
conception of containment.

00:54:29.580 --> 00:54:32.640
And indeed, that I mentioned that talk

00:54:32.640 --> 00:54:37.314
I gave at the University
at the Yale Club of Tokyo,

00:54:37.314 --> 00:54:39.760
that eventually became the little book

00:54:39.760 --> 00:54:41.750
I wrote about containment,

00:54:41.750 --> 00:54:45.160
arguing that if the Democrats
went back into office

00:54:45.160 --> 00:54:48.130
without a national security strategy,

00:54:48.130 --> 00:54:49.700
they were gonna be pushed around,

00:54:49.700 --> 00:54:53.970
as Obama was indeed pushed around in Libya

00:54:53.970 --> 00:54:56.590
because not having a
strategy and doing things

00:54:56.590 --> 00:55:00.880
like triangulation leads
you to be manipulated

00:55:00.880 --> 00:55:05.140
by people who have a clear
sense of what they want to do.

00:55:05.140 --> 00:55:09.660
And indeed, the Russians,

00:55:09.660 --> 00:55:12.633
when they went finally
into the Syrian conflict,

00:55:13.820 --> 00:55:17.280
Obama yelled had screamed
and stamped his feet

00:55:17.280 --> 00:55:20.440
but he couldn't do anything
about it, and unlike us,

00:55:20.440 --> 00:55:22.240
they had a clear strategy.

00:55:22.240 --> 00:55:26.570
Their strategy was to help
Assad win the civil war,

00:55:26.570 --> 00:55:28.250
which they then did.

00:55:28.250 --> 00:55:32.690
And so now Assad basically
has won the civil war.

00:55:32.690 --> 00:55:37.690
So we on the other hand have
no strategy in the Middle East,

00:55:38.510 --> 00:55:42.040
and this is continuing to play out today

00:55:42.890 --> 00:55:46.053
as we are watching in real-time that

00:55:46.053 --> 00:55:50.740
whatever you say about Trump's
abandonment of the Kurds,

00:55:50.740 --> 00:55:55.740
it completely, his entry
into that whole conflict

00:55:57.900 --> 00:56:01.250
is the correct observation
that the US doesn't have

00:56:01.250 --> 00:56:05.610
a strategy there and there
is no democratic regime

00:56:05.610 --> 00:56:07.340
that's being supported.

00:56:07.340 --> 00:56:09.920
The Kurds, supporting the Kurds,

00:56:09.920 --> 00:56:12.750
supporting the Kurds is
a bit like supporting

00:56:12.750 --> 00:56:15.623
the Northern Alliance in Afghanistan.

00:56:16.640 --> 00:56:18.530
The Kurds are scattered through

00:56:18.530 --> 00:56:20.530
a number of Middle Eastern countries,

00:56:20.530 --> 00:56:23.240
the Kurdistan that they
would like to build,

00:56:23.240 --> 00:56:26.820
it would involve going to
war with several of them.

00:56:26.820 --> 00:56:31.640
Turkey, for all of its appalling
behavior, is a NATO ally,

00:56:31.640 --> 00:56:33.230
the Kurds are not.

00:56:33.230 --> 00:56:37.100
As I said, one's enemy's
enemy can turn out

00:56:37.100 --> 00:56:39.930
very easily to be one's enemy.

00:56:39.930 --> 00:56:43.160
And so we have throughout the rest of the

00:56:43.160 --> 00:56:48.090
Obama administration but
really starting in 2003

00:56:48.090 --> 00:56:52.770
have had no coherent
strategy of what it is

00:56:52.770 --> 00:56:57.350
that we're actually trying to
achieve in these conflicts.

00:56:57.350 --> 00:57:01.958
And so Trump took advantage
of that and ran with it.

00:57:01.958 --> 00:57:05.810
And that's not the only fallout
from the Libyan conflict.

00:57:05.810 --> 00:57:07.560
It's quite a lot, but there's more.

00:57:08.590 --> 00:57:10.060
- As we return now to the attack

00:57:10.060 --> 00:57:12.760
on a migrant detention center in Libya,

00:57:12.760 --> 00:57:15.670
as John yang tells us
eight years of conflict

00:57:15.670 --> 00:57:18.880
and instability there are
now enmeshed with the migrant

00:57:18.880 --> 00:57:20.343
and refugee crisis.

00:57:22.010 --> 00:57:25.090
- [John] Bags of clothing
and abandoned shoes.

00:57:25.090 --> 00:57:27.710
Remnants of life strewn
throughout the blood-soaked

00:57:27.710 --> 00:57:29.240
debris of death.

00:57:29.240 --> 00:57:30.700
The early morning air strike

00:57:30.700 --> 00:57:33.270
hit the Tajoura Migrant
Detention Center in Tripoli

00:57:33.270 --> 00:57:37.130
housing some 600 people,
mostly North Africans.

00:57:37.130 --> 00:57:40.250
Emergency crews struggled
to carry away body bags

00:57:40.250 --> 00:57:41.760
through the wreckage.

00:57:41.760 --> 00:57:45.853
Survivors said they had no
warning and no protection.

00:57:53.790 --> 00:57:56.010
- [John] Libya's government
of national accord

00:57:56.010 --> 00:57:59.060
recognized by the United
Nations blamed the so-called

00:57:59.060 --> 00:58:01.800
Libyan National Army, or LNA,

00:58:01.800 --> 00:58:04.110
which is trying to seize Tripoli.

00:58:04.110 --> 00:58:06.920
The LNA acknowledged carrying
out attacks in the area

00:58:06.920 --> 00:58:09.140
but denied targeting the migrants.

00:58:09.140 --> 00:58:12.390
The LNA under the command
of General Khalifa Haftar

00:58:12.390 --> 00:58:14.980
is supported by Saudi Arabia, Egypt,

00:58:14.980 --> 00:58:17.250
and the United Arab Emirates.

00:58:17.250 --> 00:58:19.500
It controls southern and eastern Libya,

00:58:19.500 --> 00:58:21.140
but has met heavy resistance

00:58:21.140 --> 00:58:23.240
from militias defending Tripoli.

00:58:23.240 --> 00:58:27.440
Yesterday, an LNA commander
warned of intensified assaults.

00:58:27.440 --> 00:58:29.160
This is the latest calamity

00:58:29.160 --> 00:58:31.970
in eight years of chaos in Libya.

00:58:31.970 --> 00:58:34.720
Fighting has also made an
already desperate journey

00:58:34.720 --> 00:58:36.670
for migrants trying to reach Europe

00:58:36.670 --> 00:58:39.560
even more dangerous and deadly.

00:58:39.560 --> 00:58:43.490
An estimated 6,000 languish
in Libyan detention,

00:58:43.490 --> 00:58:46.770
at least half close to the
front lines of conflict.

00:58:46.770 --> 00:58:48.710
- In the last three months,

00:58:48.710 --> 00:58:52.720
Tripoli and the neighboring
areas around Tripoli

00:58:52.720 --> 00:58:54.530
have become an active war zone.

00:58:54.530 --> 00:58:57.330
So now we have migrants who
are in abysmal conditions

00:58:57.330 --> 00:58:59.670
in detention, but on top of that,

00:58:59.670 --> 00:59:02.690
they can't flee to
safer areas of the city.

00:59:02.690 --> 00:59:04.330
- [John] Many of the
migrants were rounded up

00:59:04.330 --> 00:59:05.900
by Libya's Coast Guard,

00:59:05.900 --> 00:59:08.640
trained and funded by the European Union,

00:59:08.640 --> 00:59:11.420
to prevent their crossing
the Mediterranean.

00:59:11.420 --> 00:59:14.022
- Several member states
of the EU have effectively

00:59:14.022 --> 00:59:17.038
begun criminalizing aid agencies

00:59:17.038 --> 00:59:20.760
who were providing such
and rescue services

00:59:20.760 --> 00:59:22.173
in the Mediterranean Sea.

00:59:23.360 --> 00:59:27.570
And in the absence of those
search and rescue operations,

00:59:27.570 --> 00:59:30.660
people who continue to try to flee Libya

00:59:30.660 --> 00:59:32.780
and cross the Mediterranean Sea

00:59:32.780 --> 00:59:35.020
are intercepted by the Libyan Coast Guard

00:59:35.020 --> 00:59:37.447
and returned to Libya
and are sent directly

00:59:37.447 --> 00:59:39.483
into the detention centers.

00:59:40.860 --> 00:59:44.470
- So in addition to everything else,

00:59:44.470 --> 00:59:47.530
this has fed the refugee
problem in Europe,

00:59:47.530 --> 00:59:52.060
which has fed the rise of
anti-system parties in Europe

00:59:52.060 --> 00:59:54.330
and countries like Germany.

00:59:54.330 --> 00:59:56.600
People like Angela Merkel were initially

00:59:56.600 --> 00:59:59.110
open arms for these refugees,

00:59:59.110 --> 01:00:01.800
but as we know from earlier lectures,

01:00:01.800 --> 01:00:06.030
that soon turned into
political catastrophe for her.

01:00:06.030 --> 01:00:10.410
And so this ongoing, the
externalities of this

01:00:10.410 --> 01:00:14.123
as an economist would
put it are just stunning.

01:00:16.251 --> 01:00:21.251
So those are the sort of
local and then regional

01:00:21.320 --> 01:00:26.320
and even international costs
of this, toppling this regime.

01:00:27.540 --> 01:00:30.430
So we've done a big, a deep dive into

01:00:30.430 --> 01:00:35.080
some micro stories here, things
are often not what they seem

01:00:35.080 --> 01:00:38.150
but let's now step back
a little and think about

01:00:38.150 --> 01:00:41.470
what does this mean for the
doctrine of responsibility

01:00:41.470 --> 01:00:45.430
to protect, and what are its implications

01:00:45.430 --> 01:00:50.320
for other forms of
humanitarian intervention?

01:00:50.320 --> 01:00:54.050
So thinking back to the earlier
lecture on responsibility

01:00:54.050 --> 01:00:57.900
to protect, we now have to recognize

01:00:57.900 --> 01:01:01.140
that the Kosovo operation
was misleadingly benign.

01:01:01.140 --> 01:01:04.830
It gave people much too much confidence

01:01:04.830 --> 01:01:09.830
in what can be achieved
by forcible intervention

01:01:09.890 --> 01:01:12.380
in these types of situations.

01:01:12.380 --> 01:01:17.380
First of all, in 1999, Kosovo
was already in the middle a,

01:01:19.430 --> 01:01:22.370
it was in the middle of a
civil war in a failed state,

01:01:22.370 --> 01:01:25.880
so the idea that one might
be creating a failed state

01:01:25.880 --> 01:01:29.143
by intervening was not on the table.

01:01:30.010 --> 01:01:34.010
Secondly, unlike the story in Benghazi

01:01:34.010 --> 01:01:38.130
that was mostly hype and
widely discredited at the time,

01:01:38.130 --> 01:01:41.350
if you go back and look
at the news coverage,

01:01:41.350 --> 01:01:44.850
it was undeniable that there
was ongoing ethnic cleansing

01:01:44.850 --> 01:01:48.693
and gross human rights
abuses going on in Kosovo.

01:01:50.470 --> 01:01:54.183
Third, the intervention was
brief and it seemed to work,

01:01:55.380 --> 01:01:58.820
and that led to enormous
hubris about the effectiveness

01:01:58.820 --> 01:02:03.420
of surgical power in
rearranging the furniture

01:02:03.420 --> 01:02:06.263
in the targeted regime.

01:02:07.690 --> 01:02:10.620
Another feature of it
was that NATO and the US

01:02:10.620 --> 01:02:13.650
plausibly had clean hands in Kosovo.

01:02:13.650 --> 01:02:16.303
There was nothing really
strategic at stake for them.

01:02:17.640 --> 01:02:19.730
I said it violated the NATO charter

01:02:19.730 --> 01:02:21.770
that they got involved because they were,

01:02:21.770 --> 01:02:23.570
none of them was threatened, but really,

01:02:23.570 --> 01:02:25.850
they didn't have anything
to gain out of this.

01:02:25.850 --> 01:02:30.580
So the notion that there was
some surreptitious agenda,

01:02:30.580 --> 01:02:34.621
as we've now seen there
was surreptitious agenda

01:02:34.621 --> 01:02:38.320
going on in Libya wasn't there,

01:02:38.320 --> 01:02:40.683
and it wasn't there for good reasons.

01:02:42.270 --> 01:02:45.750
Also, the Kosovo operation was before

01:02:45.750 --> 01:02:48.070
the US-led invasion of Iraq

01:02:48.070 --> 01:02:50.550
had sullied our international image.

01:02:50.550 --> 01:02:53.910
Think again to the story about Abu Ghraib

01:02:53.910 --> 01:02:56.030
that we ended with last time.

01:02:56.030 --> 01:03:00.759
We were perceived very differently in 1999

01:03:00.759 --> 01:03:05.759
across the Middle East than
we were perceived after 2003.

01:03:07.890 --> 01:03:11.740
And just to add to that,
the intervention in Kosovo

01:03:11.740 --> 01:03:13.873
had been on behalf of Muslims,

01:03:14.960 --> 01:03:18.790
so that muted criticism in the Middle East

01:03:18.790 --> 01:03:21.300
and the global south, even
though there was some,

01:03:21.300 --> 01:03:24.279
but we were, it was the Americans and NATO

01:03:24.279 --> 01:03:28.710
intervening to protect Muslims in Kosovo.

01:03:28.710 --> 01:03:32.530
So for all of those reasons,
there was much more confidence

01:03:32.530 --> 01:03:36.660
in the ability to implement R2P

01:03:36.660 --> 01:03:39.950
than we now see was warranted,

01:03:39.950 --> 01:03:44.739
but people like Samantha Power
and Susan Rice and others

01:03:44.739 --> 01:03:49.063
therefore were far too optimistic.

01:03:49.960 --> 01:03:52.640
And when we take stock,
there are really three,

01:03:52.640 --> 01:03:55.530
three big challenges
one has to think about

01:03:55.530 --> 01:03:59.580
when we're talking about
humanitarian intervention.

01:03:59.580 --> 01:04:02.930
One is big principal-agent challenges.

01:04:02.930 --> 01:04:06.360
So if you're thinking
about somebody going in

01:04:06.360 --> 01:04:10.430
to intervene in a country,
who is the right principal?

01:04:10.430 --> 01:04:11.400
Who should go in?

01:04:11.400 --> 01:04:15.810
Who should make the decision
to go in, I should say?

01:04:15.810 --> 01:04:17.653
And then who's the right agent?

01:04:18.840 --> 01:04:23.840
During the Cold War, the
sort of agreement was that

01:04:24.650 --> 01:04:28.420
the US and the Soviets
would not send people in,

01:04:28.420 --> 01:04:30.310
that's why in the Middle East,

01:04:30.310 --> 01:04:34.220
you'd get sort of Norwegian
blue hats or whatever

01:04:34.220 --> 01:04:39.220
because if you have an obvious
interest, there's a problem.

01:04:39.520 --> 01:04:42.180
But most importantly,
how does the principal

01:04:42.180 --> 01:04:43.603
control the agent?

01:04:45.156 --> 01:04:50.050
Once the UN Security Council
has authorized NATO to act

01:04:50.050 --> 01:04:54.680
and they're acting, it's
very difficult to reconvene

01:04:54.680 --> 01:04:58.080
and reverse those decisions because

01:05:00.500 --> 01:05:04.380
any one of the permanent
members can veto efforts,

01:05:04.380 --> 01:05:06.320
efforts to do that.

01:05:06.320 --> 01:05:09.550
So Brazil has been
pushing something called

01:05:09.550 --> 01:05:13.090
the Doctrine of Responsibility
while protecting,

01:05:13.090 --> 01:05:15.530
trying to create monitoring ongoing,

01:05:15.530 --> 01:05:18.480
monitoring device of interventions,

01:05:18.480 --> 01:05:21.513
but I think good luck with that.

01:05:22.640 --> 01:05:24.890
Then there are questions
about effectiveness.

01:05:27.780 --> 01:05:32.360
Peace-building is very
difficult after an intervention.

01:05:32.360 --> 01:05:35.350
If you look at the literature
that's been published by,

01:05:35.350 --> 01:05:38.160
the empirical literature
on peace-building,

01:05:38.160 --> 01:05:42.013
some of which I will post
if people are interested,

01:05:42.013 --> 01:05:45.610
it's extremely difficult to
do after an intervention.

01:05:45.610 --> 01:05:49.123
I talked about this some
in relation to Germany,

01:05:49.123 --> 01:05:52.660
West Germany and Japan after World War II,

01:05:52.660 --> 01:05:57.290
but particularly when you
go in during a civil war,

01:05:57.290 --> 01:06:01.940
again, we went in supporting
what turned out to be

01:06:01.940 --> 01:06:04.520
the losing side in a civil war

01:06:04.520 --> 01:06:06.150
and then we we basically

01:06:10.150 --> 01:06:15.110
knocked off the regime that
that had very little legitimacy,

01:06:15.110 --> 01:06:16.910
but neither did anyone else.

01:06:16.910 --> 01:06:20.650
And so peace-building operations
are extremely expensive,

01:06:20.650 --> 01:06:25.133
extremely slow, and don't work very well.

01:06:26.430 --> 01:06:29.020
Civil wars are, one of the main factors

01:06:29.020 --> 01:06:30.580
the scholarly literature shows,

01:06:30.580 --> 01:06:33.560
one of the main factors
that lengthens civil wars

01:06:33.560 --> 01:06:36.470
is often external involvement.

01:06:36.470 --> 01:06:39.130
If you look now at the civil war in Yemen,

01:06:39.130 --> 01:06:43.800
it's becoming a proxy
conflict between the Saudis

01:06:43.800 --> 01:06:47.320
and the Iranians.

01:06:47.320 --> 01:06:52.320
And so once you start supporting
one side in a civil war,

01:06:53.301 --> 01:06:57.440
the chances are, if I just come
in and support other sides,

01:06:57.440 --> 01:06:59.380
the conflict's just gonna go on,

01:06:59.380 --> 01:07:02.390
whereas if nobody gets
involved from the outside,

01:07:02.390 --> 01:07:07.380
most civil wars eventually end
in about five years or less.

01:07:09.160 --> 01:07:13.480
But they're gonna also be
huge legitimacy challenges.

01:07:13.480 --> 01:07:17.590
There's no obligation to
intervene, I've said this earlier,

01:07:17.590 --> 01:07:22.230
so it's a case-by-case discretion
for the Security Council,

01:07:22.230 --> 01:07:25.870
but that effectively creates immunity

01:07:25.870 --> 01:07:29.390
for the Security Council
members and their allies.

01:07:29.390 --> 01:07:33.283
In 2014, when Israel went into Gaza,

01:07:34.960 --> 01:07:38.490
there were widespread
allegations of R2P violations

01:07:38.490 --> 01:07:43.490
on both sides by Hamas
and by the Israeli troops,

01:07:44.650 --> 01:07:46.560
but the idea that there was gonna be

01:07:46.560 --> 01:07:48.760
some kind of humanitarian intervention

01:07:48.760 --> 01:07:51.640
of course is unthinkable when you consider

01:07:51.640 --> 01:07:55.530
the alliances of people
on the Security Council.

01:07:55.530 --> 01:07:59.010
So this doctrine is
gonna be perceived to be

01:07:59.010 --> 01:08:04.010
an instrument by which
the countries that are in

01:08:04.060 --> 01:08:06.840
the driver's seat in the Security Council

01:08:06.840 --> 01:08:11.840
are going to protect
themselves and not others.

01:08:12.870 --> 01:08:15.340
So what are the lessons?

01:08:15.340 --> 01:08:18.870
Well, one is that R2P
should remain exceptional.

01:08:18.870 --> 01:08:22.350
As I said when we were
talking about this idea of

01:08:22.350 --> 01:08:26.190
illegal but legitimate,
it's a bit like asking

01:08:26.190 --> 01:08:28.740
for forgiveness rather than permission,

01:08:28.740 --> 01:08:30.480
but you can't institutionalize that,

01:08:30.480 --> 01:08:31.730
so it should be exceptional,

01:08:31.730 --> 01:08:34.770
it should be very, very difficult to do.

01:08:34.770 --> 01:08:38.573
You need exceedingly high
thresholds for intervention,

01:08:40.140 --> 01:08:42.380
because if you intervene,

01:08:42.380 --> 01:08:45.790
if you take on a government
on its own territory,

01:08:45.790 --> 01:08:49.810
you are almost by definition gonna take,

01:08:49.810 --> 01:08:53.680
you're courting the possibility
of creating a failed state.

01:08:53.680 --> 01:08:56.430
It's important therefore
to keep force proportional

01:08:56.430 --> 01:08:58.590
to the problem.

01:08:58.590 --> 01:09:03.440
And as as within days
of 1973 being adopted

01:09:03.440 --> 01:09:05.760
by the Security Council, it was clear

01:09:05.760 --> 01:09:08.870
that the potential humanitarian
catastrophe in Benghazi

01:09:08.870 --> 01:09:13.870
was over, Gaddafi's Air Force
had been destroyed as well,

01:09:14.830 --> 01:09:19.830
and the overtures being
made by the African Union

01:09:19.960 --> 01:09:22.920
and the Arab League should
have been listened to,

01:09:22.920 --> 01:09:26.580
to negotiate some sort of ceasefire.

01:09:26.580 --> 01:09:31.010
Regime change should always
be the last and final resort.

01:09:31.010 --> 01:09:33.850
Interested players are very bad agents,

01:09:33.850 --> 01:09:35.870
but the UN doesn't have a military,

01:09:35.870 --> 01:09:38.463
so who are gonna be the agents?

01:09:40.610 --> 01:09:43.410
Peace-building, as I said, it's essential,

01:09:43.410 --> 01:09:46.590
but very difficult to do.

01:09:46.590 --> 01:09:48.960
You might say a better focus rather than

01:09:48.960 --> 01:09:52.110
responsibility to protect would be,

01:09:52.110 --> 01:09:55.370
or responsibility while protecting

01:09:55.370 --> 01:09:57.993
would be responsibility to prevent.

01:09:59.100 --> 01:10:02.770
I said to you earlier
that the crisis in Syria

01:10:02.770 --> 01:10:06.630
really starts ramping up
in 2007 and eight and nine

01:10:06.630 --> 01:10:08.010
because of the droughts.

01:10:08.010 --> 01:10:10.920
That would have been
the time to intervene.

01:10:10.920 --> 01:10:13.740
Look at a country today like Chad.

01:10:13.740 --> 01:10:17.000
It's a landlocked country
surrounded on all sides

01:10:17.000 --> 01:10:19.440
by failed states.

01:10:19.440 --> 01:10:20.813
It's oil-dependent,

01:10:22.520 --> 01:10:27.520
that makes it a prime
target, a prime candidate for

01:10:27.560 --> 01:10:32.350
this sort of collapse and
humanitarian catastrophe

01:10:32.350 --> 01:10:35.600
that we have seen in Libya and Syria.

01:10:35.600 --> 01:10:38.150
But what is anybody doing about Chad?

01:10:38.150 --> 01:10:38.983
Very little.

01:10:40.520 --> 01:10:44.323
So just to sum up,

01:10:45.250 --> 01:10:50.040
I think that, if you think over
the course of these lectures

01:10:50.040 --> 01:10:55.040
on resisting aggression across borders,

01:10:55.340 --> 01:10:58.930
it is possible to come up
with an integrated account

01:10:58.930 --> 01:11:01.560
that builds off of Kennan's insights

01:11:01.560 --> 01:11:03.870
for a post-Cold War world.

01:11:03.870 --> 01:11:07.670
And I take the three
elements of his view to be

01:11:07.670 --> 01:11:09.740
economize on the use of force,

01:11:09.740 --> 01:11:12.600
keep it sufficient but proportional.

01:11:12.600 --> 01:11:15.380
Don't destroy the village
in order to save it,

01:11:15.380 --> 01:11:17.580
the famous line from Vietnam.

01:11:17.580 --> 01:11:21.600
Always remember that
the biggest challenge is

01:11:21.600 --> 01:11:23.920
and the most important battle to win

01:11:23.920 --> 01:11:26.090
is the battle for hearts and minds,

01:11:26.090 --> 01:11:29.390
not the military confrontation,

01:11:29.390 --> 01:11:33.260
that is not gonna create
a governable country.

01:11:33.260 --> 01:11:37.350
And stop the bully without becoming one.

01:11:37.350 --> 01:11:39.240
This idea to prevent domination,

01:11:39.240 --> 01:11:41.690
but without yourselves dominating.

01:11:41.690 --> 01:11:44.680
Machiavelli says at the
outset of the discourses,

01:11:44.680 --> 01:11:47.430
he says the reason he favors democracy

01:11:47.430 --> 01:11:50.040
is that the elites want to dominate,

01:11:50.040 --> 01:11:53.210
and the common people
want not to be dominated.

01:11:53.210 --> 01:11:55.410
So this is the idea of prevent domination

01:11:55.410 --> 01:11:57.543
without becoming a dominator.

01:11:58.917 --> 01:12:01.710
And if you wanted to sort of
draw a conceptual map here

01:12:01.710 --> 01:12:04.233
of resisting aggression across borders,

01:12:06.000 --> 01:12:08.200
you could do something like this.

01:12:08.200 --> 01:12:10.690
You could say, well think about domination

01:12:10.690 --> 01:12:12.080
that crosses borders.

01:12:12.080 --> 01:12:15.840
First, there's self-defense,
if a country attacks you,

01:12:15.840 --> 01:12:17.523
that's the strongest case.

01:12:18.450 --> 01:12:20.520
Classic containment, you want to prevent,

01:12:20.520 --> 01:12:22.313
you want to head that off,

01:12:24.270 --> 01:12:27.770
a country that's in the
position to do that.

01:12:27.770 --> 01:12:30.640
So I think Kennedy during
the Cuban Missile Crisis

01:12:30.640 --> 01:12:33.483
gradually ramping up enough,

01:12:36.350 --> 01:12:39.843
the embargo and so on, that is the way to,

01:12:43.490 --> 01:12:46.270
to prevent threats to the
homeland, if you like.

01:12:46.270 --> 01:12:48.994
Make war a strategy of last resort,

01:12:48.994 --> 01:12:53.410
and ramp it up, ramp up
hostility proportionately.

01:12:53.410 --> 01:12:56.330
If you're going in to
defend a third party,

01:12:56.330 --> 01:12:58.341
as we did in Kuwait,

01:12:58.341 --> 01:13:03.341
in Iraq, when Iraq went
into Kuwait in 1991,

01:13:03.501 --> 01:13:06.200
then we should be thinking
about containment again

01:13:06.200 --> 01:13:10.302
first of all authorization,
there needs to be authorization.

01:13:10.302 --> 01:13:13.820
That could be invitation
from a legitimate government,

01:13:13.820 --> 01:13:16.000
as was the case in Kuwait,

01:13:16.000 --> 01:13:18.650
or it could be external authorization

01:13:18.650 --> 01:13:20.793
through something like the UN.

01:13:21.940 --> 01:13:24.000
When we're thinking about crossing borders

01:13:24.000 --> 01:13:25.703
to resist domination,

01:13:28.020 --> 01:13:30.170
there's got to be a higher threshold,

01:13:30.170 --> 01:13:32.420
because the stakes are so much higher

01:13:32.420 --> 01:13:36.660
because once you're a crossing
border in order to resist

01:13:36.660 --> 01:13:38.380
or to prevent domination,

01:13:38.380 --> 01:13:40.680
that might be better to
say than resist there,

01:13:42.250 --> 01:13:45.010
you're inevitably courting the possibility

01:13:45.010 --> 01:13:47.010
of creating a failed state.

01:13:47.010 --> 01:13:50.250
So with responsibility to protect,

01:13:50.250 --> 01:13:52.215
there must be the imminent danger

01:13:52.215 --> 01:13:55.320
of human rights violations,

01:13:55.320 --> 01:13:57.720
there must be external authorization,

01:13:57.720 --> 01:14:00.190
there must be a diverse coalition,

01:14:00.190 --> 01:14:04.380
there must be a limited mandate
which it should be observed

01:14:04.380 --> 01:14:09.380
as was done in 1991 in
Iraq, but not in 2003,

01:14:10.800 --> 01:14:15.163
and regime change should be
the absolute final resort.

01:14:16.610 --> 01:14:20.100
What about intervening
to install democracy?

01:14:20.100 --> 01:14:22.070
This is the most ambitious of all.

01:14:22.070 --> 01:14:25.680
We're not intervening, this
is a neoconservative dream,

01:14:25.680 --> 01:14:29.310
not just to stop particular
human rights violations,

01:14:29.310 --> 01:14:31.890
but actually to produce regime change.

01:14:31.890 --> 01:14:35.960
And there, first of all,

01:14:35.960 --> 01:14:38.440
there's no point in trying
to install democracy

01:14:38.440 --> 01:14:41.140
in a country where the
plausible economic conditions

01:14:41.140 --> 01:14:43.360
don't exist, we know what they are,

01:14:43.360 --> 01:14:46.240
per capita income of about $14,000,

01:14:46.240 --> 01:14:51.240
a diverse economy being
the two most important.

01:14:51.921 --> 01:14:53.910
There must be an opposition

01:14:53.910 --> 01:14:57.710
that is predominantly indigenous.

01:14:57.710 --> 01:14:59.970
Part of the problem with Ahmed Chalabi,

01:14:59.970 --> 01:15:03.410
he had been living in London for decades,

01:15:03.410 --> 01:15:05.826
and when things didn't work out in Iraq,

01:15:05.826 --> 01:15:07.523
he could go back to London.

01:15:09.330 --> 01:15:11.418
But he did go back and forth to London

01:15:11.418 --> 01:15:13.810
when things got bad for him.

01:15:13.810 --> 01:15:17.938
You really want the indigenous
opposition because they have,

01:15:17.938 --> 01:15:20.175
it's like you want the pilot on the plane.

01:15:20.175 --> 01:15:24.570
You want people for
whom if this goes badly,

01:15:24.570 --> 01:15:27.710
they're gonna pay the
price before you go in

01:15:29.860 --> 01:15:32.500
and help them, or try to help them.

01:15:32.500 --> 01:15:34.930
You must have some credible conviction

01:15:34.930 --> 01:15:36.863
that they're capable of governing,

01:15:38.280 --> 01:15:41.850
and some credible conviction

01:15:41.850 --> 01:15:44.370
that they're likely to be democratic.

01:15:44.370 --> 01:15:49.370
So even if and when one side
wins in this Libyan civil war,

01:15:51.570 --> 01:15:55.430
there's no guarantee that
it's going to be democratic.

01:15:55.430 --> 01:15:59.150
Indeed, it seems vanishingly unlikely

01:15:59.150 --> 01:16:01.980
that that would be the case.

01:16:01.980 --> 01:16:05.890
So I think, if you want to
sort of think conceptually

01:16:05.890 --> 01:16:09.980
about what should be
guiding policy thinking

01:16:09.980 --> 01:16:13.200
about humanitarian and
other forms of intervention,

01:16:13.200 --> 01:16:16.600
it would look something like
that in a post-Cold War,

01:16:16.600 --> 01:16:20.090
which would ramp up the
stakes appropriately

01:16:20.090 --> 01:16:24.330
as the risks and costs
of failure accelerate.

01:16:24.330 --> 01:16:27.930
But the big problem we now face

01:16:27.930 --> 01:16:30.280
in addition to all the others is that

01:16:31.350 --> 01:16:35.033
the catastrophe in Libya
has more or less left R2P

01:16:36.480 --> 01:16:40.260
in tatters internationally.

01:16:40.260 --> 01:16:43.170
It'd be very difficult to do this again.

01:16:43.170 --> 01:16:48.070
And America has greatly
diminished its capacity to act

01:16:48.070 --> 01:16:49.863
throughout the Middle East.

01:16:51.370 --> 01:16:55.090
I'm seeing Russia has
expanded to fill the vacuum,

01:16:55.090 --> 01:17:00.090
and that is the sort of big
geopolitical story is that

01:17:00.150 --> 01:17:02.800
capacity to be influential in the region

01:17:02.800 --> 01:17:07.610
is much less than it was the
day before George W. Bush

01:17:07.610 --> 01:17:12.610
intervened in Iraq in March of 2003.

01:17:13.520 --> 01:17:16.920
So it's in that sense a
big withdrawal by the US,

01:17:16.920 --> 01:17:19.410
and Russia filling the void.

01:17:19.410 --> 01:17:24.090
We will see on Tuesday
another kind of withdrawal

01:17:24.090 --> 01:17:26.573
by the US that has been,

01:17:27.470 --> 01:17:31.110
had other forms of void being filled,

01:17:31.110 --> 01:17:35.150
particularly with China's
involvement in Africa.

01:17:35.150 --> 01:17:36.353
We'll see you then.

01:17:37.738 --> 01:17:40.155
(soft music)

